div.p:
St. Austine took off this scruple long ago; 
                  Sol. 

               In tempor alibus angustiis per hominem subvenit Deus, salus tua ipse est, per angelum subvenit Deus, salus ipse tua est; 'Tis true, (saith he) By a man, or by an Angel, God doth sometimes save, but still it is God himself who is the salvation; men and Angels are but his finger, his instruments; the authority to save, and the efficacie of saving, are still proper to God.

Thus have I dispatched as much of the Text, as the time and your patience can well afford me leave; 
                  Ʋse. 
                I will now descend to the usefull applications of all this to our present occasion, and then I shall conclude.

1. It was a remembrance of us in our low estate: O give thanks to the God of heaven, who remembred us in our low estate,
               Psal. 136.23.
               for his mercy endureth for ever. It was a salvation after a three-fold humbling:
